<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hata Stresses Parties' Need To Compromise </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2812134693 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 28 Dec 93 
Morning Edition p 3 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2812134693 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] During a YOMIURI SHIMBUN interview on 27 December, 
Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party] leader Tsutomu Hata, who is 
deputy prime minister and concurrently foreign minister, 
speaking on the outlook for deliberations on the political 
reform bills said: "Since the electoral system is an issue 
regarding rules in a democracy, meetings should be held (between 
ruling and opposition parties) to mutually discuss ways to reach 
a compromise." He thus reiterated the need for ruling and 
opposition parties to reach a compromise for the passage of the 
political reform bills. 
  Concerning the view expressed by some politicians that the 
lower house of the Diet should be dissolved if the political 
reform bills fail to become law during the current Diet session, 
Hata said: "We should be ready and willing to do just that." 
However, he also said: "Dissolving the Diet is not such a 
simple matter." 

</TEXT>

