<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ichikawa Opposes Major Revision of Reform Bills </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2812133593 Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 28 Dec 93 
Morning Edition p 7 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2812133593 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In a news conference held on 27 December, Komeito 
Secretary General Yuichi Ichikawa expressed a negative attitude 
toward further concessions on the political reform bills. 
Commenting on recent remarks by Deputy Prime Minister and 
Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata, who has showed a flexible stance 
toward major revisions of the political reform bills, Ichikawa 
said: "Different approaches could be possible if the Liberal 
Democratic Party [LDP] is ready to accept our concessions 
without boycotting Diet deliberations. Under the present 
circumstance, it is difficult for coalition parties to allow 
further concessions on the main points of the bills." 
  It is believed that Ichikawa's remarks were made in view of 
opinions among Social Democratic Party of Japan [SDPJ] members. 
The quota for single-seat constituencies was already increased 
from 250 to 274 when the bills passed the lower house, and the 
SDPJ would certainly oppose a further increase. 
  As an example of concessions, Hata proposed dividing a 
nationwide constituency for the proportional representative 
election into several regional blocs; however, Ichikawa noted: 
"Not only the LDP, but also each party in the coalition would 
have various opinions on the design of the regional constituency 
blocs. If we set our hands on this issue, it would take at 
least 40 days to reach an accord. I do not think it is a 
realistic idea." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

