<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Finance Ministry Considers Selling NTT Shares </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW3012141993 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 24 Dec 
93 Morning Edition p 1 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW3012141993 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Ministry of Finance [MOF] plans to include 
revenues from sales of government-held shares in Nippon 
Telegraph and Telephone Corporation (NTT) in a draft budget for 
fiscal 1994. It is considering selling 500,000 shares. There is 
criticism that "the MOF places priority on selling NTT shares 
held by the government." However, the MOF appears to think this 
criticism will weaken because a ban on selling NTT shares is to 
be lifted at the end of fiscal 1993 and because it included the 
resumption of public capital increase in measures to deregulate 
the stock market, which the ministry recently announced. It 
will decide whether or not to sell the shares while carefully 
watching the trend of the stock market. If the MOF sells the 
shares, it will be the first time it has done so in six years. 
  The ministry will put the revenues from the sales in the 
debt 
consolidation fund. Although the fund is for repaying national 
debts, part of it will be used for public works projects. The 
ministry plans to estimate the revenue amount by examining NTT 
share prices in the market. If the share price keeps to the 
level of the closing price at the Tokyo Stock Exchange on 22 
December (which was 751,000 yen), the profit will be about 300 
billion yen after a selling charge is deducted. 
  The MOF hopes to spend part of the revenue on public works 
projects to shore up the economy. 
  Nonetheless, it thinks that the stock market is in a severe 
situation. That is why it dropped plans last weekend to list 
Japan Tobacco Inc. shares on the stock market in the current 
fiscal year. Thus, it is still uncertain if the MOF will 
actually sell NTT shares. 
  After giving up selling NTT shares in fiscal 1989, the 
government planned to sell 500,000 shares each year over a 
five-year period starting in fiscal 1991. However, because the 
stock market continued to be sluggish, it hesitated to sell the 
shares. In August 1992, the government announced the freeze on 
the sales of NTT shares in fiscal 1992 and 1993. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

