<H5>  Cabinet Support Rate Remains High </H5>
  The Hosokawa cabinet still maintains a high level of public 
support four months after its inauguration. Under the LDP 
ruling, the cabinet support rate moved in parallel with the LDP 
support rate. However, under the Hosokawa administration, the 
popularity of the JNP and the coalition parties is in decline 
while the administration itself receives broad support. In 
other words, high public support for the cabinet is due to 
Hosokawa's personal popularity. 
  The LDP support rate remains at 22 percent, or the lowest 
level since the beginning of the survey. Only farmers, 
fishermen, and those over 60 years in age offered support of 
over 30 percent. Support for LDP President Yohei Kono is also 
dropping. 


------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|Table 5. Do you feel you are living in comfort compared with the same period | 
|in the previous year? (indicated in percents)                                | 
------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|Yes                      |No Change                |No                       | 
------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 
|3.5                      |57.9                     |38.1                     | 
------------------------------------------------------------------------------- 


  [Text]Changes in Livelihood 
  After the inauguration of the Hosokawa administration, a 
larger proportion of the public feel more satisfied about 
politics; however, changes in people's livelihood are not 
favorable. During the period from January 1991 to September 
1993, people did not feel the influence of the recession. 
However, since October a greater number of pollees began to 
answer that their living conditions were "becoming worse." If 
things are left as they are, the Hosokawa administration may 
lose its popularity. This reminds me of former U.S. President 
George Bush's failure to win reelection. He had the support of 
90 percent of the public immediately after the Gulf war, but the 
support rate dropped quickly due to the recession. 


