<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   IAEA Waiting for DPRK Response on Inspections </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0701005094 Seoul YONHAP in English 0044 GMT 7 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0701005094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Berlin, Jan. 6 (YONHAP) -- North Korea has not sent 
the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) any message 
signalling its acceptance of IAEA inspections of its nuclear 
sites, IAEA Spokesman Hans Meyer said Thursday [6 January]. 
  The Vienna-based IAEA is waiting for Pyongyang to provide an 
official message signed by Atomic Energy Industry Minister Choe 
Hak-kun for any kind of breakthrough in the situation in view of 
past negotiations with the communist regime, Meyer said. 
  There has not been any message from Pyongyang since 
unofficial contact between working-level officials from each 
side on Wednesday [5 January], he said. But IAEA expects North 
Korean response regarding nuclear inspections soon and will 
continue to be on the alert this weekend, he added. 

</TEXT>

