<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Economic Conference With U.S., Canada, Mexico Eyed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0801084094 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 8 Jan 94 
Morning Edition p 5--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0801084094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The idea of setting up a quadrilateral economic 
conference for promoting free trade has cropped up among Japan, 
the United States, Canada, and Mexico. The four countries have 
begun studying the idea with the Japanese Foreign Ministry 
playing a leading role. They are expected to hold the first 
working-level meeting as early as mid-1994. It is likely that 
the proposed conference will be in the form of an unrestricted, 
loose consultative organization to study issues such as 
quadrilateral cooperation on economic policies and what the 
Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation (APEC) conference ought to be 
like. 
  The idea is based on a report worked out in 1992 by the 
Japan-Mexico Committee Toward the 21st Century--which was 
established by the governments and private sectors of the two 
countries. Concrete details of the idea will be discussed from 
now on. The idea has been formulated with the enforcement of 
the North American Free Trade Agreement [NAFTA] taken into 
consideration. Moreover, there are concerns about the U.S. 
attitude of giving priority to bilateral talks other than 
multilateral talks when trying to solve trade issues. 
  The Japanese Government intends to make the quadrilateral 
conference a "stage for multilateral dialogue and consultations 
to enhance economic cooperation and study ways of dealing with 
trade disputes." However, the government has no intention of 
producing a free trade zone like NAFTA that could be 
discriminatory against nonmember nations. 
  As the first summit meeting of the APEC was held in November 
1993, cooperative relations within the Asia-Pacific region have 
strengthened. However, Japan and the Association of Southeast 
Asian Nations (ASEAN) have expressed concern that NAFTA will 
lead to a bloc economy. Although Malaysia has proposed the idea 
of establishing the East Asian Economic Caucus (EAEC), the 
United States and other countries, which are excluded from the 
idea, have opposed it. In this way, discord still remains 
within APEC. 
  Because it is certain that Japan will play a leading role if 
the economic conference is established, the idea is likely to 
arouse the interest of neighboring countries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-47032 </DOCNO>
