<H3> <TI>   Vice Foreign Minister on Prospects for Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1001105994 Tokyo KYODO in English 1044 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1001105994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 10 KYODO -- Vice Foreign Minister 
Kunihiko Saito denied reports Monday [10 January] that Japan is 
pessimistic about the prospects for framework trade talks with 
the United States. 
  Saito told a press conference that it is "clearly a 
misunderstanding" to assume that Japan has lost its drive in the 
trade talks. 
  He pointed out that there is still a month before February 
11 
when Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa and U.S. President Bill 
Clinton meet in Washington. 
  Japan and the United States have promised to come up with an 
agreement on the bilateral framework trade talks by then. 
  Little progress has been reported so far on the talks, which 
is being held under the Japan-U.S. trade framework accord 
concluded last July. 
  Saito also said the trade negotiations are "two-way talks" 
and are not aimed at having Japan alone make concessions. 
  He said there are various points where the United States 
should compromise and called for Washington's continued efforts 
to boost its competition and to reduce its financial deficit. 
  Specifically, Saito urged some U.S. states to further open 
their markets to foreign companies and businesses, saying 
markets in some of the U.S. states are "not as open as some 
foreign countries desire" because of the difference in systems 
from state to state. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

