<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo, Washington `Widely Divided' on Auto Issue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0801091794 Tokyo KYODO in English 0907 GMT 8 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0801091794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 8 KYODO -- Japan and the United States 
remain widely divided on automobile trade as they were prepared 
to start negotiations on the issue next week, Japanese 
Government officials said Saturday [8 January]. 
  The four-day subcabinet-level negotiations will begin in 
Tokyo on Tuesday under an agreement to work out a new framework 
for bilateral trade. 
  The officials said Washington insists on a tough stand 
concerning auto and auto parts trade, pressing Japan to make 
further concessions to open its automobile market wider to 
imports. 
  The negotiations will focus on a U.S. demand that Japan set 
a numerical target for imports of U.S.-built cars and parts, 
they said. 
  In previous sessions of the talks, the United States 
proposed 
that the Japanese Government ask Japanese automakers to extend 
their programs for imports of U.S.-made auto parts beyond fiscal 
1995 and that the Japanese and U.S. Governments work out rough 
measures setting the value of Japanese imports of finished cars 
and parts from the United States in the future. 
  Sluggish automobile sales at home and overseas have made it 
difficult for the Japanese auto industry to compromise on the 
U.S. stance, the officials said. 
  They said Washington will find it equally difficult to back 
down on its stand as automobile trade accounts for a large 
portion of its trade deficit with Japan. 
  The officials said the negotiations may drag on toward a 
February 11 summit between Japanese Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa and U.S. President Bill Clinton. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

