<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   MITI To Lift Restraints on Auto Exports to U.S. </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0801014594 Tokyo KYODO in English 0127 GMT 8 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0801014594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 8 KYODO -- Japan plans to stop its 
self-imposed quota on passenger car exports to the United States 
after the fiscal 1993 quota expires March 31, government sources 
said Saturday [8 January]. 
  The export quota, first imposed in fiscal 1981 amid growing 
friction between Japan and the U.S. over auto trade, is set at 
1.65 million vehicles for fiscal 1993. 
  But since fiscal 1987, Japan's car exports to the U.S. has 
fallen short of the quota, as Japanese automakers were boosting 
production at U.S. plants. 
  The Ministry of International Trade and Industry is to make 
a 
final decision on whether to eliminate the voluntary restraint 
after consulting with domestic automakers and reviewing ongoing 
bilateral trade talks on autos and auto parts, the sources said. 
  As the "Big Three" U.S. automakers are regaining the 
competitive edge from the Japanese, their executives have voiced 
support for scrapping the export quota, despite stalled 
bilateral talks on auto and auto parts trade. 
  Under the so-called framework negotiations, Tokyo and 
Washington remain at odds over the numerical targets demanded by 
Washington, but rejected by Tokyo, to measure progress in market 
opening. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

