<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo Seeks To Enhance Ties With NATO </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0801074194 Tokyo KYODO in English 0632 GMT 8 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW0801074194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 8 KYODO -- Strengthening ties with the 
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO) is becoming a major 
task for Japan's diplomacy, Foreign Ministry officials said 
Saturday [8 January]. 
  The Foreign Ministry aims to boost Japan's ties with NATO 
this year by cosponsoring a seminar in Europe and hosting a 
high-level political and security dialogue in Tokyo, they said. 
  Japan's increasing interest in ties with NATO reflects 
concern over the strong showing of nationalists in Russia's 
recent elections, the problem of control over nuclear weapons in 
Ukraine, and other uncertainties in the political situation of 
the former Soviet Union. 
  The officials said the two forums will focus particularly on 
the unstable situation in Russia, which is the most crucial 
issue commonly facing Japan and NATO. 
  In addition, Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata is expected to 
reschedule his postponed trip to NATO headquarters in Brussels 
for July, just prior to the annual summit that month of the 
Group of Seven (G-7) industrialized nations in Naples. 
  Hata was originally scheduled to make the visit this month, 
but postponed it due to the extension of the current Diet 
session. 
  Japan has also begun participating in meetings of the 
Conference on Security and Cooperation in Europe (CSCE) with a 
special status short of full membership. 
  The officials said closer ties with such European bodies, in 
addition to expanding opportunity for dialogue on issues of 
mutual concern, will be of benefit to Japan as it considers how 
to enlarge its contribution to international efforts now under 
way in the former Yugoslavia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

