<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   MITI To Stop Promotion of Would-Be Politicians </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1001083294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0730 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1001083294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 10 KYODO -- The Ministry of 
International Trade and Industry (MITI) will stop the 
controversial practice of promoting officials who are about to 
quit government service to run in elections, its vice minister 
said Monday [10 January]. 
  The move comes shortly after a high-ranking MITI bureaucrat 
resigned following the trade minister's intervention in such a 
case. 
  Vice Minister Hideaki Kumano said at a press conference that 
the ministry will exercise impartiality in personnel changes 
even for officials intending to enter politics. 
  "We will strictly refrain from creating a new post for an 
official who plans to quit for elections, for example, so as not 
to cause suspicion of any special consideration on the 
assumption of transfer to the political world." 
  Late last December, Masahisa Naito resigned as director 
general of the ministry's Industrial Policy Bureau following 
conflict with MITI Minister hiroshi kumagai. 
  The minister had urged Naito to resign, saying he had shown 
favoritism in promoting a junior when Naito was director general 
at the minister's Secretariat. 
  Naito contended at his last press conference that he could 
not understand nor accept Kumagai's reasons for demanding his 
resignation, saying, "the promotion in question followed MITI's 
conventional practice." 
  Such promotions are regarded as boosting the curricula vitae 
of prospective political candidates. 

</TEXT>

