<H3> <TI>   Keidanren Chief Hiraiwa Says Yen Should Drop </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1001095094 Tokyo KYODO in English 0933 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1001095094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 10 KYODO -- The yen should decline 
against the dollar to reflect economic fundamentals, Gaishi 
Hiraiwa, chairman of the Federation of Economic Organizations 
(Keidanren), said Monday [10 January] . 
  Hiraiwa said at a press conference the yen's further drop 
will help stimulate Japan's economy, pointing out that the 
United States has hoped that Japan's economic recovery would 
also benefit the U.S. economy. 
  His remark was made following a comment by U.S. Treasury 
Secretary Lloyd Bentsen last week warning Tokyo against relying 
on a weaker yen. 
  "Allowing the yen to slide is not an acceptable way out of 
recession for Japan," Bentsen said. 
  The dollar closed in Tokyo on Monday at 111.73 yen, down 
0.75 
yen from last Friday. 

</TEXT>

