<F P=103> OW1001075094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 10 KYODO -- Japan's potential and 
desirable economic growth is in the lower half of the 3 percent 
level, a high-ranking trade ministry official said Monday [10 
January]. 
  Vice International Trade and Industry Minister Hideaki 
Kumano 
said at a press conference, "I don't think our potential to 
attain 3 percent level economic growth has changed so much," 
despite the current business conditions. 
  While noting cyclic factors, Kumano stressed the need for 
implementation of middle- and long-term policies, both 
macroeconomic and microeconomic, so as to realize the nation's 
economic potential in the 21st century. 
  Kumano said the recent drop in the yen's value against the 
U.S. dollar on foreign exchange markets was not yet enough from 
the viewpoint of corporate profitability. 
  "Companies were a bit relieved by the recent trend toward a 
weaker yen, but you should not be too optimistic," Kumano said. 

</TEXT>

