<H3> <TI>   Announcement Expected `Around' 20 Jan </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1001042394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0334 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1001042394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 10 KYODO -- The government still 
intends to unveil an additional economic stimulus package around 
January 20 despite slow progress in talks among the ruling 
coalition parties on specifics, Chief Cabinet Secretary 
Masayoshi Takemura said Monday [10 January]. 
  "As of today, we still intend to unveil it by around January 
20," the government's top spokesman told a news conference. 
  He cited the talks among the ruling parties and Diet debate 
on political reform as potential stumbling blocks to the release 
of the new measures to stoke up the languishing Japanese economy. 
  Asked if the package will include income tax cuts, Takemura 
said the government will take high public expectations of such 
cuts into account in working out details of the pump-priming 
measures. 
  Earlier Monday, a government source predicted the government 
will have to delay the announcement of the additional stimulus 
measures beyond January 20 because of conflicting views in the 
coalition on whether the consumption tax, now standing at 3 
percent, should be raised to finance proposed income tax cuts. 
  The source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the 
timing of the announcement of the income tax reduction should be 
decided by February 11, when Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa is 
scheduled to meet U.S. President Bill Clinton in Washington. 

</TEXT>

