<H3> <TI>   Official Says 3d Extra Budget Schedule Undecided </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1001091894 Tokyo KYODO in English 0902 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1001091894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 10 KYODO -- The schedule for a third 
supplementary budget for fiscal 1993 has yet to be fixed, Vice 
Finance Minister Jiro Saito said Monday [10 January]. 
  The Finance Ministry [MOF] cannot begin to formulate the 
budget unless a specific framework of economic stimulus measures 
being worked out by the Economic Planning Agency is made clear, 
Saito told a press conference. 
  The third extra budget will be formed to finance additional 
public works projects and other fiscal steps expected in the 
pump-priming package to help the Japanese economy out of the 
long slump. 
  Saito avoided comment on whether or not his ministry will 
allow issuance of deficit-covering government bonds to fund 
proposed income tax cuts. 
  The MOF will respect the conclusion on the matter to be made 
by a joint economic forum between the government and ruling 
coalition parties, he said. 
  The ministry, which had been adamant about hiking the 
consumption tax to offset income tax cuts and against the 
issuance of deficit-covering bonds, reportedly softened its 
stance on the issue recently. 

</TEXT>

