<H3> <TI>   Broader Land-Tax Exemptions Considered </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1001093094 Tokyo KYODO in English 0847 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1001093094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 10 KYODO -- Broader exemptions to the 
land-holding tax are being considered as a way to stimulate the 
stagnant economy, government sources said Monday [10 January]. 
  The tax, introduced January 1, 1992, is aimed at curbing 
Japan's astronomically high land prices. 
  The business community has called for the tax to be scrapped 
or its rate of 0.3 percent to be lowered. 
  While refusing to accept these calls, the Finance Ministry 
has decided to increase the exemptions from the tax. 
  Points being considered are a cut in the tax burdens on 
holders of land which is open to the public, public parking lots 
or sites for urban development, the sources said. 
  They said the plan will substantially ease the tax burden on 
retailers, financial institutions, realtors and the leisure 
industry, which pay hefty taxes at present because much of their 
land is located in big cities. 

</TEXT>

