<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   IAEA-DPRK Talks on Nuclear Issue Reported </TI></H3>
<H4>   Disagreement on Issues Noted </H4>
<F P=102> SK0801002194 Seoul YONHAP in English 0010 GMT 8 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0801002194 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Berlin, Jan. 7 (YONHAP) -- The International Atomic 
Energy Agency (IAEA) held its first official working-level 
contact with North Korea in Vienna on Friday on inspection of 
North Korean nuclear facilities, the IAEA announced. 
  The meeting was attended by Yun Ho-chin, a councilor at the 
North Korean Embassy in Vienna, and two other North Korean 
diplomats and by inspectors at IAEA Headquarters. The meeting 
lasted for two hours from 4 in the afternoon, it said. 
  "There had been the working-level contact (between North 
Korea and the IAEA) on problems related to inspection of North 
Korea's reported nuclear facilities," IAEA spokesman Hans Meyer 
said. "The two sides agreed to continue their contact early next 
week." 
  It has been reported that the two sides agreed in principle 
that they will resolve problems related to inspection activities 
through negotiation. 
  Sources said the North Korean officials conveyed Pyongyang's 
official position but the two sides could not reach any 
agreement on the scope and number of inspections or on the size 
of the inspection team and date of its visit to North Korea. 
  One North Korean official described Friday's meeting as 
"very 
productive," however, and said that there are some items left 
for further discussion and the two sides have decided to solve 
the problems, according to an IAEA official. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

