<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   IAEA-DPRK Talks on Nuclear Issue Reported </TI></H3>
<H4>   `Several More Meetings' Needed </H4>
<F P=102> SK1001020994 Seoul YONHAP in English 0159 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1001020994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Vienna, Jan. 9 (YONHAP) -- The International Atomic 
Energy Agency (IAEA) and North Korea, which had a working-level 
contact Friday, will need several more meetings to reach an 
accord on full-scope inspections of North Korea's seven declared 
nuclear sites. 
  One of these meetings will be early this week, possibly on 
Monday, an IAEA official said Sunday on condition of anonymity. 
  In Friday's meeting, North Korea said it would open just 
five 
of its nuclear facilities to IAEA inspectors. This was a 
reversal of the agreement reached in principle late last year 
with the United States on full inspections of all seven declared 
sites. 
  It is also a far cry from the IAEA demand for inclusion in 
the full-scope inspections of what are seen by the IAEA as two 
key facilities, a radiochemical laboratory (virtually a nuclear 
fuel reprocessing facility) and a 5-megawatt reactor, the 
official said. 
  The difference will be discussed in future meetings, in 
which 
inspection of the two key facilities will be a key issue along 
with the timing of the inspections and strength of the 
inspection team. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

