<F P=100> Cambodia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ranariddh, Hun Sen at Meeting on Tourism Aims </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0801084394 Phnom Penh National Voice of Cambodia Radio 
Network in Cambodian 0430 GMT 8 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0801084394 </F>
<F P=104>  Phnom Penh National Voice of Cambodia Radio 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Cambodian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] On the afternoon of 5 January at the office of 
the Council of Ministers, a meeting was held to discuss the 
organization and development of tourism in the Kingdom of 
Cambodia [KOC] in 1994 under the lofty chairmanship of Prince 
Krompreah Norodom Ranariddh, first prime minister; and His 
Excellency [H.E.] Hun Sen, KOC second prime minister. 
  Addressing the meeting H.E. Veng Sereivut, minister of the 
Council of Ministers and state secretary of the Tourism 
Ministry, informed the meeting of the plans, organization, and 
development of tourism in 1994, during which the Tourism 
Ministry will give priority to three zones: Siem Reap-Angkor, 
Sihanoukville, and Phnom Penh City. He said that, according to 
the plans, the three airports in these zones will be expanded 
and improved, and routes will be opened and security provided 
along all roads throughout the KOC, particularly the routes 
along Angkor Thom to Banteay Srei temples. Electricity will be 
provided in Phnom Penh City and the other two cities. Guards 
will be posted at temples and guides and interpretors provided 
at each temple. Felling trees in the Angkor area will 
immediately be stopped. The Siem Reap River will be dredged and 
hotels will be given a Cambodian character. Visa formalities 
will be made easier for tourists and guests. Attention will be 
paid to improving Kep resort. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

