<F P=100> Thailand </F>
<H3> <TI>   Loggers Get Cambodian Government Extension </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0901125794 Bangkok BANGKOK POST in English 9 Jan 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> BK0901125794 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok BANGKOK POST </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Thai businessmen involved in logging in Cambodia 
will have until March 31 to bring out their wood under the 
deadline extended by the Phnom Penh government, according to a 
report brought to the attention of state agencies last week. 
  Thai Government sources said the new deadline was discussed 
at a joint meeting of representatives of the Interior and the 
Foreign ministries, the National Security Council, the Army the 
Customs and Forestry departments and the Immigration Police. 
  The Foreign Ministry told the meeting that Cambodian Finance 
Minister Sam Rangsi had informed them that Phnom Penh had 
extended the deadline from December 31 to March 31. 
  The Interior Ministry asked the Foreign Ministry to confirm 
the new deadline to enable it to extend the opening of temporary 
border passes to allow importation of the wood. 
  The meeting agreed it would help Thailand if agencies 
involved were able to negotiate with Phnom Penh to extend new 
logging concessions to Thai businessmen after the deadline. 
  Thailand now needs 9.4 million cubic metres of wood 
annually. 
It has been importing three million cubic metres each year. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

