<F P=100> Thailand </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official Discusses Agency for Burmese Refugees </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0801150494 Bangkok Radio Thailand Network in Thai 1200 GMT 
8 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0801150494 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok Radio Thailand Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Thai </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Khachatphai Burutphat, deputy secretary general of 
the National Security Council [NSC], talks about the problem of 
Burmese refugees fleeing the danger of war into Thailand's 
border areas since 1984. He says there are about 50,000 of them 
in Tak Province, 10,000 in Kanchanaburi Province, and several 
thousands in Mae Hong Son and Prachuap Khirikhan Provinces. 
Under the original plan, these people will be sent back to 
Burma once the situation has improved and there is no fighting. 
But they have not been sent back yet because they claim that 
the situation in Burma is never safe for them. 
  The NSC deputy secretary general said these Burmese refugees 
have been here for more than 10 years now. They received help 
from seven or eight private organizations, the so-called NGO 
[preceding word in English], which have been allowed to carry 
out operations without strict control by Thai authorities. Some 
of those NGO officials are involved in political activities with 
the refugees. Certain organizations used Thailand, which has 
diplomatic relations with Burma, as a transit point for certain 
leaders of the resistance ethnic minority groups to leave for a 
third country where they can launch resistance activities 
against the Burmese Government. Such an act could affect 
relations between Thailand and Burma as well as security along 
the Thai border. 
  In order to promptly control these refugees, Khachatphai 
Burutphat said that concerned authorities would form an 
apparatus in order to oversee these people. At the beginning, 
existing officials will be told to take strict action against 
them. The new agency to be set up will deal with these refugees 
based on humanitarian principles, but it will not permit them to 
engage in any kind of activities in violation of Thai law or 
activities which will affect security along the Thai-Burmese 
border. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-47118 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas006_m_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-006 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  10 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Thailand </F>
<H3> <TI>   Liu Huaqing-Led PRC Military Delegation Visits </TI></H3>
<H4>   Received by Prime Minister </H4>
<F P=102> BK0901132794 Bangkok XIN ZHONG YUAN RIBAO in Chinese 7 Jan 
94 p 16 </F>

<F P=103> BK0901132794 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok XIN ZHONG YUAN RIBAO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] A Chinese military delegation led by General Liu 
Huaqing, vice chairman of the Chinese Central Military 
Commission, arrived in Bangkok yesterday for a six-day goodwill 
visit to Thailand at the invitation of the Thai Supreme Command. 
  At 1647 yesterday, his majesty the king granted an audience 
to Gen. Liu Huaqing, who was accompanied by Supreme Commander 
Air Chief Marshal Woranat Aphichari, at the grand place. 
  At 1700, Prime Minister Chuan Likphai received Gen. Liu 
Huaqing and his entourage at Government House. 
  During the talks, Gen. Liu Huaqing thanked the prime 
minister 
and the Supreme Command for the warm reception accorded to his 
delegation. He felt greatly honored by an audience with his 
majesty the king. 
  Gen. Liu Huaqing said that his delegation's visit to 
Thailand 
is aimed at promoting friendly relations between the Thai and 
Chinese peoples. He stressed that the friendship between the 
Thai and Chinese peoples is fraternal. 
  Gen. Liu Huaqing also praised Thailand's rapid economic 
development. China is devoting itself to construction in all 
fields and is giving special attention to economic reform. 
  Gen. Liu Huaqing stressed that China's military buildup is 
aimed at self-defense. China will never seek hegemony. Like 
Thailand, China hopes to see peace and stability in the 
Asia-Pacific region. On the occasion, he also conveyed Chinese 
Prime Minister Li Peng's best regards to Prime Minister Chuan. 
  Prime Minister Chuan welcomed the visit of Gen. Liu Huaqing 
and his delegation to Thailand. He said that the Chinese 
military leader's visit to Thailand will further promote 
relations between Thailand and China, especially closer military 
contacts. 
  Prime Minister Chuan praised the achievements in China's 
construction. He said that China has experience and capability 
in producing weapons. Thailand still needs to buy weapons from 
China. He said that he had visited the Shanghai Zhonghua 
Shipyard to observe the construction of Thai ships during his 
recent visit to China. Chuan praised China for playing a vital 
role in maintaining peace and stability in the Asia-Pacific 
region, especially its contribution to the restoration of peace 
in Cambodia. It was commendable that China also achieved the 
fastest economic growth rate in the world last year. 
  After the talks, Prime Minister Chuan conferred the Order of 
the Knight, First Class, on Gen. Liu Huaqing for his important 
contributions to the friendly relations between the armed forces 
and peoples of the two countries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

