<F P=100> Vietnam </F>
<H3> <TI>   Pham The Duyet Discusses Social Priorites </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK1001131794 Hanoi Vietnam Television Network in Vietnamese 
1215 GMT 9 Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1001131794 </F>
<F P=104>  Hanoi Vietnam Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Vietnamese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Hanoi Labor, War Invalids, and Social Welfare 
Agency met on 7 January to evaluate its work performance for 
1993 and initiate its tasks for 1994. Attending the function 
were Comrade Pham The Duyet, member of the Political Bureau and 
secretary of the Hanoi party committee, and representatives of 
the Ministry of Labor, War Invalids, and Social Welfare and 
other concerned sectors. 
  In 1993, the Hanoi Labor, War Invalids, and Social Welfare 
Agency patterned its action program after the city's political 
tasks and 10 fundamental orientations. Thanks to well-defined 
guidelines and positive steps, the agency gave advice to local 
party committee echelons and administrative organs on ways to 
ensure the positive implementation of labor, war invalid, and 
social welfare policies. Satisfactory steps have been taken to 
generate jobs. More than 20 billion dong has been drawn from 
different public funds to create jobs for 33,500 unemployed 
people. A total of 181 households with 345 working people have 
been sent to various new economic zones. 
  Due effort has been made to look after the well-being of war 
invalids and survivors of fallen combatants. Altogether, 91 
houses have been built and 4,265 savings accounts have been 
opened for distribution to families that rendered meritorious 
service to the revolution. Furthermore, 560 seriously ill 
soldiers and 60 parents with two or more children listed as 
fallen combatants have undergone treatment or been admitted to 
nursing homes. The agency has also made extra efforts to 
educate and provide vocational training to drug addicts and 
prostitutes. 
  In 1994, the agency will work out a program to eliminate 
hunger and reduce poverty. It is expected that by 1995, no 
family in the city will be affected by hunger. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

