<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   South Opposition Demands Arms Case Reinvestigation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1001063994 Pyongyang KCNA in English 0443 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1001063994 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, January 10 (KCNA) -- South Korean 
opposition parties denounced the puppet Army-prosecution joint 
investigation headquarters which concluded an arms import 
scandal as a "mere fraud", according to a radio report from 
Seoul. 
  6.7 million dollars disappeared in 1992 and some 1,300 
million South Korean won in 1991 when the puppet Defence 
Ministry was dealing with a French company over the import of 
ammunitions. 
  The (?seamy) side of the case was disclosed in December last 
year. The puppet Army-prosecution joint investigation 
headquarters clinched off the case as a "mere fraud" committed 
by a South Korean arms broker and a French arms dealer vis-a-vis 
the logistics headquarters of the puppet Defence Ministry. 
  The Democratic Party in a commentary January 7 branded the 
joint investigation headquarters' behavior as ridiculous, and 
urged the invocation of the "parliamentary investigation power" 
in order to probe the truth of the case. 
  The national party in a statement demanded that the 
"government" nullify the results of investigation of the 
headquarters and appoint a special prosecutor to make a full 
reinvestigation into the case. 

</TEXT>

