<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK, Japan Normalization Talks `Likely To Resume' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0901051594 Seoul YONHAP in English 0506 GMT 9 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0901051594 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 9 (YONHAP) -- Normalization talks 
between Japan and North Korea, suspended for more than a year, 
are likely to resume next month at the earliest, the TOKYO 
SHIMBUN here reported on Sunday. 
  Quoting an official working with the Japanese delegation to 
the talks, the paper said that if the meeting were actually 
resumed, the time would most likely be some time in February 
shortly before or after the third-round U.S.-North Korea 
high-level talks expected to take place next month. 
  The report said North Korea expressed the willingness to 
return to the talks during the visit to Pyongyang by Hajime 
Fukata, a Dietman and organization director of the Japan 
Socialist Party, late last year. 
  Fukata had talks with Hwang Chang-yop, North Korean Workers' 
(Communist) Party international affairs director, during his 
stay in Pyongyang. 
  The normalization talks were last held in November 1992 in 
Beijing when the meeting broke up after Japan demanded a probe 
to determine whether a woman named "Yi Un-hoe" who allegedly 
taught Japanese language to terrorist Kim Hyon-hui was a 
Japanese woman. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

