<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Press Comments on U.S. Nuclear Talks With North </TI></H3>
<H4>   THE KOREA TIMES Editorial </H4>
<F P=102> SK0801091794 Seoul THE KOREA TIMES in English 8 Jan 94 p 6 </F>
<F P=103> SK0801091794 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul THE KOREA TIMES </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed editorial: "No Concessions to North Korea"] </F>
  [Text] We are paying close attention to news reports that 
North Korea has agreed to only a one-time international 
inspection of seven declared nuclear sites but has avoided a 
much more serious issue -- IAEA [International Atomic Energy 
Agency] access to undeclared sites, especially two nuclear waste 
dumps needed to verify clearly whether Pyongyang has been 
building nuclear weapons. 
  At this moment we do not expect the U.S. to knuckle down to 
the crafty ploys of Pyongyang, whose words have been seen in the 
past to bear absolutely no relation with its intentions. Nor 
will it allow North Korea to wring out of it concessions in 
their negotiations because it will also have learned that the 
North, if given an inch, will take a mile. 
  Despite the reported accord, as U.S. Secretary of State 
Warren Christopher pointed out Thursday [6 January] in an 
interview, the U.S. and its allies still face some difficult and 
sensitive steps before they reach the goal of regular 
inspections and a nuclear-free Korean peninsula. 
  As far as the nuclear issue is concerned, the fundamental 
question is whether North Korea has really cast aside its 
intention to go nuclear. We are particularly suspicious of what 
appears to be North Korea's strategy to sidestep the crucial 
issue by allowing only an inadequate single inspection. 
  It cannot be denied that North Korea has delayed things as 
long as possible anticipating a slip in the basic U.S. position 
on North Korea which it will exploit for all it is worth. 
  In this connection, both the U.S. and the IAEA must play 
their cards carefully in their separate talks with North Korea, 
not unilaterally giving in to North Korea's persistent demand 
for U.S. diplomatic recognition and cancellation of the Team 
Spirit military exercise. We stand to lose more than we gain if 
we resort to a hasty approach in dealing with North Korea. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

