<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Citizens Coalition Delivers Farm Policy Recommendation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1001034094 Seoul YONHAP in English 0256 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1001034094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 10 (YONHAP) -- Leaders of the Citizens' 
Coalition for Economic Justice [CCEJ] delivered a policy 
recommendation to Prime Minister Yi Hoe-chang on Monday morning 
that criticises the government's handling of the Uruguay Round 
[UR] trade talks. 
  CCEJ Secretary-General So Kyong-sok said that there had been 
problems during the Uruguay Round talks, and he called on the 
government to take measures to revive agriculture and rural 
economy in coping with rice market opening. 
  So said the lack of experts caused by frequent reshuffles of 
concerned public officials, the absence of an active negotiating 
strategy and the lack of investment in rural areas during 
negotiations were problems noticed in the course of handling the 
UR talks. 
  The government should fully support farmers' and fishermen's 
organizations and the fund for this support should be supplied 
by the non-agricultural and urban sectors, the policy 
recommendation says. 
  While predicting farm products market opening will affect 
not 
only related industries such as fertilizer, farm machinery and 
farm products processing but living conditions in urban areas 
because of migration to cities, it calls on the government to 
take measures as early as possible. 

</TEXT>

