<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry To Restructure Trade Negotiators </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0801022294 Seoul YONHAP in English 0044 GMT 8 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0801022294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 8 (YONHAP) -- The Foreign Ministry 
plans to restructure its trade negotiation team, installing 
bureaus for multilateral economic and environmental issues, 
officials said Saturday. 
  One of the additions, which has been tentatively named the 
"Economic Cooperation and Environment Bureau," will handle talks 
with developing countries. 
  The "Economic Organizations Bureau" will take up 
multilateral 
negotiations such as the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade 
(GATT), World Trade Organization (WTO), Organization for 
Economic Cooperation and Development (OECD) and U.N. Development 
Program (UNDP). 
  The current International Trade Bureau will be responsible 
for bilateral trade negotiations with added functions in 
aviation and maritime talks, officials said. 
  The changes will be proposed to President Kim Yong-sam in 
the 
ministry's New Year report Jan. 21. 
  The ministry is considering hiring Koreans with foreign 
citizenship for the new bureaus to promote South Korean 
participation in multilateral trade organizations, according to 
the officials. 
  This plan calls for hiring 50 to 100 people of Korean 
ancestry with degrees in economics and professional backgrounds 
in related fields. They will be placed at the foreign and other 
ministries. 

</TEXT>

