<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Defense Dissolves Arms Joint Investigation Team </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK0801080094 Seoul YONHAP in English 0524 GMT 8 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK0801080094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 8 (YONHAP) -- The Defense Ministry on 
Saturday [8 January] dissolved the joint military-prosecution 
investigation team that was formed to look into an arms purchase 
fraud, and gave the military prosecution the task of hunting 
down the suspected masterminds -- Chu Kwang-yong and Jean-Rene 
Fuan. 
  Chu, Korean agent of the French arms dealer, is believed to 
be either in the United States or Northeast Asia. He fled the 
country Dec. 15. 
  The military prosecution is seeking to catch Fuan in a way 
that minimizes international diplomatic friction, and will 
consult with the Foreign Ministry and maintain close ties with 
law-enforcement agencies in countries such as France. 
  The military prosecution freed an Army colonel and Navy 
captain in charge of overseas procurement at the Defense 
Logistics Agency on Saturday, suspending the charges against 
them. 
  The duo are Col. Yun Sam-song, head of the agency's overseas 
procurement office, and Capt. To Chong-il, a division chief in 
Yun's office. 
  The two officers and a Defense Ministry civilian, who was 
also released, will be referred to a disciplinary panel, a 
Ministry source said. 
  The Ministry said Friday [7 January] the probe had revealed 
that the 6.7 million-U.S.-dollar shell fraud was the product of 
a conspiracy between Fuan and Chu. 

</TEXT>

