<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Discolored Rice Found in Thai Shipment </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1001074394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0714 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1001074394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Hakodate, Hokkaido, Jan. 10 KYODO -- Grains of 
rice which may have been discolored by mold have been found in 
an emergency shipment of rice from Thailand, Hokkaido 
Prefectural Government officials said Monday [10 January]. 
  The discolored rice was discovered in a 5,775-ton shipment 
of 
long-grain rice for food processing that arrived from Bangkok at 
Hakodate Port on January 1. 
  Inspectors found the discolored rice in some of the 
50-kilogram bags that are being unloaded from a 
Panamanian-registered freighter. A total of 1,400 tons of the 
rice had been unloaded through Sunday. 
  The Hakodate Bureau of the Hokkaido Food Office was not 
certain if the discolored rice was like that when it left 
Thailand or if it became discolored during the trip to Japan. 
  The officials said that the rice was not discolored by the 
kind of mold caused by condensation that was found in imported 
rice from Thailand at the port of Maizuru, Kyoto Prefecture last 
month. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

