<F P=100> Cambodia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sihanouk on Anti-Vietnamese `Struggle', Rights </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0801133493 Hong Kong AFP in English 1315 GMT 8 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK0801133493 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Phnom Penh, Jan 8, (AFP) -- King Norodom 
Sihanouk has defended Cambodia's human rights record, denying 
that the rights of the country's ethnic Vietnamese are abused. 
  Sihanouk, in a statement released by state news agency AKP 
Saturday, said that apart from Pol Pot's Khmer Rouge, the only 
anti-Vietnamese pogroms took place after the then Prince 
Sihanouk was ousted in a 1970 US-backed coup d'etat led by 
General Lon Nol. 
  "The non-Khmer Rouges patriotic Cambodians only struggled 
against the Vietnamese agressors but never allowed the human 
rights of civilian Vietnamese men and women to be violated," 
Sihanouk, who is undergoing surgery for cancer in Beijing, said. 
[passage omitted] 
  Sihanouk said an "Australian personality" made the 
accusation 
during an interview with BBC television. 
  Sihanouk turned the accusation around, asking: "Were the 
white Australians themselves perfectly irreproachable in their 
policies and acts towards the (non-white) ethnic minority who 
were the original owners of Australia?". [passage omitted] 
  Some 20,000 ethnic Vietnamese fishing people fled Cambodia 
in 
the run-up to last May's U.N.-supervised elections to escape a 
Khmer Rouge campaign of ethnic cleansing. [passage omitted] 
  Although many of the families could speak Khmer and had 
fished the waters of the Tonle Sap, Cambodia's great lake, for 
generations and others were married to Cambodians, they found 
themselves stranded as the government would not let them return. 
  Sensitive to the effectiveness of Khmer Rouge propaganda, 
the 
government said it first needed to draft an immigration law. 
  But months later, Minister of Information Ieng Mouli said no 
decision had been made on whether the boat people could return 
as the law had yet to be discussed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-47177 </DOCNO>
