<F P=100> Philippines </F>
<H3> <TI>   Trade Embargo Against South Africa Lifted </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK1001023094 Manila BUSINESS WORLD in English 5 Jan 94 p 10 </F>
<F P=103> BK1001023094 </F>
<F P=104>  Manila BUSINESS WORLD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Genevieve L. Soledad] </F>
  [Text] The Philippine Government has lifted all forms of 
trade restrictions against South Africa, the Department of Trade 
and Industry announced yesterday. 
  Trade and Industry Undersecretary Tomas I. Alcantara said 
the 
resumption of trade ties with South Africa will jack up the 
exchange of trade between the two countries to $200 million this 
year from the existing cap of $50 million. 
  He added that Filipino businessmen can also use South Africa 
as an entry point for exports to central African countries, 
adding that Filipino exporters can already go into 
oleochemicals, garments, electronics, and software. 
  South Africa can then ship in its exports of steel, coal, 
phosphate rock, and capital equipment. 
  Moreover, the lifting of the trade embargo would also mean 
the flow of South African investments into the country, said Mr. 
Alcantara. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-47179 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas006_n_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-006 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  10 Jan 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Vietnam </F>
<H3> <TI>   Do Muoi Receives U.S. Senate Delegation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK0901112894 Hanoi Voice of Vietnam in English 1000 GMT 9 
Jan 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK0901112894 </F>
<F P=104>  Hanoi Voice of Vietnam </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] During a reception given in Hanoi to the 32-member 
U.S. Senate delegation led by Senator Johnston, Vietnamese party 
General Secretary Do Muoi wished that the U.S. make a further 
effort to improve the relations between the two countries. 
  Meanwhile, Senator Johnston said that the relations between 
the two countries have reached an important point and nowadays 
the U.S. should choose either normalize of relations or 
maintaining its sanction against Vietnam. He said the 
normalization of the U.S.-Vietnamese relations in economic and 
cultural fields will not only be in the interests of the two 
peoples but also influence world and regional peace and 
stability. 
  A press conference was held in Hanoi on Sunday afternoon by 
U.S. Senator Johnston and his party. Senator Johnston commented 
that the Vietnamese government and people have been cooperative 
in most of the ways, and the way of the world cooperation is not 
by punishment and the punishment ought to be stopped and start a 
new chapter [sentence as heard]. He said there is a tremendous 
vitality and energy in Vietnam. He hoped that his party and 
himself will make further efforts to consolidate and develop the 
cooperative relations between the two countries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

