<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kim yong-sun Said Charged With U.S. Affairs </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1001141494 Tokyo KYODO in English 1035 GMT 10 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1001141494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, Jan. 10 KYODO -- North Korea has placed a 
sacked official of its governing Korean Workers Party in charge 
of U.S. affairs, informed Western sources in seoul said Monday 
[10 January]. 
  Kim Yong-sun, who was sacked as a candidate Politburo member 
in December, has been placed in charge of affairs with the 
United States, the sources said. 
  Kim met with U.S. Undersecretary of State Arnold Kanter in 
New York in January 1992 for the highest level contact ever 
between the two nations to discuss concerns arising from North 
Korea's suspected program to develop an atomic arsenal. 
  North Korea and the U.S. held two rounds of talks at the 
vice ministerial level last June and July aimed at resolving the 
impasse over international inspections of North Korea's 
suspected nuclear facilities. 
  Pyongyang has indicated a desire to upgrade the contacts 
after the third round meeting, which has not yet been held. 
  Kim, who has served in a number of foreign relations 
positions in the Workers Party and in the government over the 
years, was removed as a candidate Politburo member in a party 
reshuffle last month. 
  Meanwhile, the vice chairman for the party's section on 
reunification of the Korean peninsula, Kang Chu-il, was placed 
in charge of working-level affairs with South Korea, which had 
been directed by Kim, the sources said. 
  They expected little change in Pyongyang's South Korea 
policies in the wake of Kang's appointment. 
  With the recent political revival of Kim Yong-chu, the 
younger brother of North Korean President Kim Il-song, there 
have been reports that the younger Kim would have a special hand 
in South Korean affairs. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

