<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   More on Telecommunications Meeting With U.S. </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0701044894 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 7 Jan 
94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0701044894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 7 Jan 94 </F>
Morning Edition] 
  [Text] The working group meeting on government procurement 
in the telecommunications sector held in Washington on 4 and 5 
January closed without making any significant progress. While 
there has been some progress on the issue of improving the 
transparency of the bidding procedures, Japan rejected the U.S. 
proposal to include Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corporation 
(NTT) in the agreement on government procurement, and the two 
sides have not been able to close the gap on the issue of 
objective criteria. 
  Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa will be meeting President 
Bill Clinton for the third time at the summit talks on 11 
February. The Clinton administration seems to have refrained 
from making tough demands on Japan so far "for fear of hurting 
the Hosokawa administration." However, the present government 
has been in existence for six months, and the prime minister's 
close aides believe that "this time, they will be asking for 
results." The government is, thus, hoping that some progress 
can be made in the framework talks, which is the focal issue at 
present. 
  According to one government source, however, "the point of 
compromise remains unclear," and more rough sailing is expected 
in the talks. 
  As far as Hosokawa is concerned, he has no choice but to 
push 
for "political reform first," even though he also faces the need 
to adopt pump-priming measures and pass the budget, not to 
mention his visit to the U.S. In contrast to Clinton, who will 
be well- prepared, Hosokawa cannot claim to have fully prepared 
a well-thought-out strategy for the U.S. summit meeting. 
  At the framework talks, government procurement, insurance, 
and automobiles and auto parts have been named as priority 
areas, and both sides expect to reach agreement before the 
summit meeting in February. After the negotiations on 
telecommunications, the working group on government procurement 
of medical equipment is holding meetings on 6 and 7 January, the 
working group on insurance on 10 and 11 January, and deputy 
ministerial level discussions on automobiles and auto parts are 
due to start on 11 January, leading up to the critical 
negotiating phase in February. 
  According to the Ministry of International Trade and 
Industry, objective criteria still represent a controversial 
issue because "they might lead to managed trade." The United 
States would like to introduce such things as future sales 
volume as numerical targets, while Japan is strongly opposed to 
the idea. Recently, according to the Office of the U.S. Trade 
Representative, the United States has taken the more flexible 
position of "not seeking the setting of numerical targets." 
Japan, however, remains unconvinced. It believes "the United 
States is still asking for an increase in our purchase of 
U.S.-made automobiles and auto parts; this will still lead to 
numerical targets." 
  Furthermore, in government procurement and insurance, the 
United States is seeking to measure the degree of openness of 
the Japanese market by comparing the share of foreign products 
and companies on it to those in the other G-7 nations. 
According to the Foreign Ministry, Japan maintains it will "not 
agree to any targets," on this issue either. 
  However, since Japan has been unable to come up with any 
effective measures to reduce its current accounts surplus, some 
government officials believe "Japan will have to make some sort 
of concession." In the end, Hosokawa may have to make a 
political decision overriding the wishes of the bureaucrats. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-47193 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas005__a94006" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-005-A </AU>
