<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   More on Planned Subjects for Hata's PRC Trip </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW0701140194 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 7 Jan 94 
Morning Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW0701140194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tsutomu Hata, deputy prime minister and foreign 
minister, is scheduled to visit China from 8 January. A Foreign 
Ministry source said on 6 January that during a meeting with his 
Chinese counterpart Qian Qichen, Hata would confirm the gravity 
of security dialogue between Japan and China, and ask China to 
disclose as much military information as possible because ASEAN 
nations have expressed apprehensions over China's moves to 
strengthen its military power. Specifically, Hata is 
considering asking China to compile a "defense white paper" in 
accordance with international standards, the source said. 
  In recent years, China has increased its annual defense 
budget by two digits, has claimed rights over the Spratly 
Islands, and has intensified its activities in the waters near 
the islands. 
  Hata plans to tell the Chinese Government that Japan is 
interested in how China's military power will change. At the 
same time, he will ask China to use the "Japanese-Sino Security 
Council" as a place to open its military power to the world. 
The council held the first meeting of foreign ministerial 
officials of both countries in Beijing on 20 December. It is 
said that Hata plans to make those requests because he believes 
the repeat of frank exchanges of views between the two countries 
will lead to substantial multilateral security talks. 

</TEXT>

