<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hata Promises Stance of `Independence' in Trade Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1101035294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0310 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1101035294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 11 KYODO -- Japan will take spontaneous 
actions rather than depend on foreign pressure to conclude the 
stalled framework trade talks with the United States, Foreign 
Minister Tsutomu Hata said Tuesday [11 January]. 
  Hata told a news conference that there are priority areas in 
the ongoing trade framework talks with the United States and 
that Tokyo wants to do its utmost to come up with good results. 
  Japan will negotiate with the United States with 
independence 
and will keep in mind the improvement of Japanese living 
standards, and not just place importance on its relation with 
the United States, he said. 
  Hata also called for U.S. efforts in bringing the bilateral 
talks to a successful conclusion. 
  He countered U.S. calls for Japan to boost market shares of 
foreign goods to the level of other industrialized nations, 
saying there is agreement on free trade. 

</TEXT>

