<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kumagai Rejects Solution of Managed Trade </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1101032594 Tokyo KYODO in English 0300 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1101032594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 11 KYODO -- Japan's trade minister 
suggested Tuesday [11 January] that Tokyo will reject U.S. calls 
for administrative guidance to reduce its trade surplus. 
  International Trade and Industry Minister Hiroshi Kumagai 
said at a press conference, "We cannot practice managed trade or 
allow administrative guidance only to reduce the surplus with 
the United States by using double standards at home and abroad." 
  "The government of (Prime Minister Morihiro) Hosokawa is 
trying to create transparency in markets," Kumagai said. 
  Referring to reported U.S. criticism that bilateral trade 
framework negotiations have faced hard going due to Japan's 
bureaucracy, Kumagai said that bluff or dissatisfaction may be 
expressed when negotiations reach the final stage. 
  "At least, I don't think the Ministry of International Trade 
and Industry insists on its own logic being accepted," Kumagai 
said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

