<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Senator Voices Hope on Trade Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1101074094 Tokyo KYODO in English 0723 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1101074094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 11 KYODO -- A U.S. senator voiced hope 
Tuesday [11 January] that Japan and the United States can 
achieve some progress in bilateral trade talks in February, a 
Foreign Ministry official said. 
  Sen. John Rockefeller IV said in a meeting with Prime 
Minister Morihiro Hosokawa that the U.S. Congress will focus its 
attention on a meeting between President Bill Clinton and 
Hosokawa scheduled for February 11 as a "checkpoint" of 
bilateral trade ties, the official said. 
  The Democratic senator elected from West Virginia also 
reportedly said the U.S. legislature hopes the two leaders can 
chart a new future course for U.S.-Japanese trade relations at 
the planned talks. 
  The statement apparently means the U.S. Congress wants some 
progress in trade negotiations between Washington and Tokyo, 
which are being held under the bilateral trade framework 
agreement reached last July. 
  While acknowledging the importance of progress in the trade 
negotiations, Hosokawa touched on the need for efforts from both 
sides, the official said. 
  Calling Clinton and Hosokawa reform-oriented leaders, 
Rockefeller said he is pleased with Hosokawa's emergence as a 
new leader in Japanese politics and that he wants to be a friend 
of the premier, according to the officials. 
  Rockefeller told reporters after the meeting that his talks 
with the premier were "just a private conversation." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

