<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian Kuril Islands Group Visits Sapporo </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1101061294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0550 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1101061294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Sapporo, Jan. 11 KYODO -- Visa-free exchanges of 
visits between Russians from a group of disputed islands off 
Hokkaido and Japanese have brought Russian islanders to a point 
where they no longer view Japan as an enemy state, the leader of 
a delegation of islanders said Tuesday [11 January]. 
  Kuril District Administration Chief G. Dolin, assessing the 
results of two years of visa-exempt exchanges, said, "the fact 
that we islanders have stopped viewing Japan as an enemy is the 
most important change." 
  Speaking at a press conference in Sapporo, the capital of 
Hokkaido, Dolin said friendships have developed between Russians 
and Japanese, while the views of the Russians on the territorial 
dispute have moved closer to those of the Japanese. 
  The Russian delegation arrived in Sapporo on Sunday for a 
six-day stay in Hokkaido and Tokyo to coordinate a plan for 
visa-free group exchanges between neighboring regions of the two 
countries this year. 
  South Kuril District Chief N.A. Pokidin pledged at the press 
conference that efforts would be made to expand access for 
former Japanese residents and their relatives to graves dating 
from before the Russian takeover of the disputed islands. 
  The four islands -- Kunashiri, Etorofu, Shikotan and the 
Habomai islets -- were seized by Soviet forces at the end of 
World War II and subsequently repopulated by Russians. 
  Russian refers to them as the South Kurils, while Japan 
calls 
them its northern territories. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-47205 </DOCNO>
