<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hosokawa Lauds Ukraine Removal of Nuclear Arms </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1101031394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0230 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1101031394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 11 KYODO -- Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa on Tuesday [11 January] welcomed Ukraine's tentative 
agreement to completely remove nuclear weapons from its soil. 
  "That is a very fine thing," Hosokawa told reporters. 
  Hosokawa's remarks came after U.S. President Bill Clinton 
announced Monday in Brussels that Ukraine will sign an agreement 
with Russia and the United States on Friday on the scrapping of 
its 176 intercontinental ballistic missiles and 1,800 warheads. 
  A government source noted that the fate of nuclear weapons 
left on Ukrainian soil after the disintegration of the Soviet 
Union has served for some time now as a source of anxiety. 
  The source called it "good news" that Ukraine will agree to 
remove them. 
  But when asked about the prospect for Japanese technical or 
financial assistance in helping Ukraine with that task, the 
source replied that no such assistance is planned. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

