<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo To Host Population, Development Forum </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1101110194 Tokyo KYODO in English 0959 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1101110194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, Jan. 11 KYODO -- Japan will cosponsor an 
eminent persons' meeting on the subjects of population and 
development on January 26 and 27 in Tokyo, Foreign Ministry 
spokesman Terusuke Terada said Tuesday [11 January]. 
  The meeting will formulate its recommendations to a 
UN-sponsored conference in Cairo next September. 
  Some 20 high-level scholars, academics and political leaders 
who are well-versed in the problems of population will attend 
the meeting at the UN University in Tokyo, Terada said. 
  Participants will include such prominent figures as 
Norwegian 
Prime Minister Gro Harlem Brundtland, former Mexican President 
Miguel de la Madrid, former World Bank President Robert McNamara 
and Taro Nakayama, former Japanese foreign minister. 
  The meeting is to be held under the cosponsorship of the 
U.N. 
Population Fund (UNFPA), the UN University and the Foreign 
Ministry. 
  Japanese Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa will address the 
opening ceremony. 
  The participants are expected to adopt a Tokyo declaration 
on 
the closing day. 
  The deliberations at the meeting will be recommended to the 
U.N.-sponsored International Conference on Population and 
Development, which is to be held in Cairo in September to 
discuss measures for problems related to the rapidly increasing 
world population. 
  Terada said Japan is by far the largest donor country for 
UNFPA, donating 59 million dollars in 1992 and as much as 63 
million dollars in 1993. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

