<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Team Inspects UN-Protected Area in Croatia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1101045294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0433 GMT 11 Jan 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1101045294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Zagreb, Jan. 11 KYODO -- A Japanese fact-finding 
mission to the former Yugoslavia on Monday [10 January] 
inspected a United Nations protected area and a refugee center 
in Croatia. 
  The eight-member Foreign Ministry mission is looking into 
possible areas for an expanded Japanese contribution to the 
international efforts under way in the former Yugoslavia. 
  Shunji Yanai, director general of the ministry's Foreign 
Policy Bureau, said there is much Japan ought to do in the way 
of humanitarian assistance, such as helping with refugee camps. 
  He suggested that Japan could also help with reconstruction 
after the conflict is over. 
  The team, which left Japan last Friday, visited an inland UN 
protected area that is one of four such demilitarized sites set 
up in Croatia. 
  They also crossed a cease-fire line between Croatian and 
ethnic Serbian forces and visited the country's border with 
Bosnia-Hercegovina at the Sava river. 
  At each site, the Japanese were briefed by local officers of 
the UN protection force. 
  On Tuesday, the mission will visit the besieged Bosnian 
capital of Sarajevo and meet officials of the government there. 
They will also visit the Serbian capital of Belgrade and the 
Macedonian capital of Skopje before returning to Japan on 
January 17. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

